<br>
Affirmative Opening Statement: &quot;Resolved:According to the Bible, baptism is not essential for salvation. The Bible shows in detail how salvation is to take place. What is the real transformation that takes place at salvation? What is the purpose of baptism? These are questions that are essential for either side to answer for this debate, and I will attempt to answer them with the Bible as my main source. However, let me prelude my case with a quote from Francis Schaeffer-&quot;Our Confession of Faith, Chapter 28, Section 5, makes it very clear that our subordinate standards do not teach Baptismal Regeneration: &quot;Although it be a great sin to condemn or neglect this ordinance, yet grace and salvation are not so inseparably annexed unto it, as that no person can be regenerated or saved without it, or that all that are baptized are undoubtedly regenerated.&quot; <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#DEB887><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/bsparrowshearth.showUserPublicProfile?gid=whitetigress2004>whitetigress2004</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle><span style=color:green;><b>The Poet</b></span></span><br>  Posts: 85<br> <font color=#B87333>(10/12/03 10:06 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fsparrowshearthfrm21.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=6.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Challenge #1 debate- Is baptism necessary for salvation?</span><hr size=1> Ah *smiles* nicely done, darkmast :)<br>
 <br>
K, here is my intro : Baptism must be, as he says, clearly defined during the beginning of this debate: it is a point upon which both of our arguments surely pivot. Using the KJV Bible as my main source, i hope to &quot;prove&quot; that Baptism is and has been, since the death of our Lord and Saviour, necessary for salvation. Also, it would do well for the audience to keep in mind that this is a *fun* debate. It is my hope that, overall, the accomplishment of this debate is study of God's word and spiritual enlightenment for all of us :)<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#F5F5DC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/bsparrowshearth.showUserPublicProfile?gid=darkmast03>darkmast03</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle><span style=color:green;> <b>The Dark Knight and <br>Torchbearer of the Tournaments!</b></span></span><br>  Posts: 17<br> <font color=#B87333>(10/13/03 1:56 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fsparrowshearthfrm21.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=6.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Affirmative Case #1</span><hr size=1> Ephesians 2:8-9 &quot;For by grace are ye saved through faith; and that not of yourselves: [it is] the gift of God: Not of works, lest any man should boast.&quot; Let's analyze this verse for a minute. &quot;For by grace are ye saved through faith...&quot; Well, what does grace mean? Grace according to Merriam Webster is 1) a : unmerited divine assistance given humans for their regeneration or sanctification 2.) a : Approval, favor. So, we are &quot;saved&quot; by grace, that is, God's approval spawned &quot;through faith.&quot; Faith, according to Hebrews 11:1, &quot;is the substance of things hoped for, the evidence of things not seen.&quot; So, God forgives us because of our faith in Him. Perhaps the easiest evidence of this comes from Rom 10:9 which states quite clearly &quot;That if thou shalt confess with thy mouth the Lord Jesus, and shalt believe in thine heart that God hath raised him from the dead, thou shalt be saved.&quot; <br>
    <br>
Notice the common theme that is NOT present in these verses. Works is not a factor. In fact, not once is baptism even alluded to. You can even keep going with this thought and see in the Ephesians verse that, in fact, &quot;works&quot; cannot be a part of salvation &quot;lest anyone should boast.&quot; Let's look at this in relation to Jesus. I think we could all agree that Jesus never had to be saved. The virgin birth made it clear that Jesus did not have a &quot;sin nature&quot; that He had to be saved from. Now, why then was Jesus baptized? Well, it is evident at the end of the baptism. Jesus received the blessing of God in the shape of a dove. This then, is the purpose of baptism. It relates us with Christ and, ultimately with God.  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#DEB887><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/bsparrowshearth.showUserPublicProfile?gid=whitetigress2004>whitetigress2004</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle><span style=color:green;><b>The Poet</b></span></span><br>  Posts: 88<br> <font color=#B87333>(10/15/03 4:19 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fsparrowshearthfrm21.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=6.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Affirmative Case #1</span><hr size=1> I would like to point out that nowhere does Dark say, with proof, that baptism is a work: yes, we are baptised with water, but who is to say that it isn't just as much spiritual as physical-to use dark's own example, Christ was baptised, and when He was, He received the Holy Ghost, as seen in Luke 3:22: and the Holy Spirit descended on him in bodily form like a dove: surely the recieving of the Spirit is not purely physical? Is it then not logical that perhaps it is baptism in combination with faith that saves us? When Christ tells Nicodemus in John 3:5, &quot;He who is not born of water and of the Spirit cannot enter into the kingdom of God,&quot; it is entirely possible that He is talking of water baptism and spiritual baptism. <br>
<br>
Notice carefully the exact wording of the verse darkmast quoted: Hebrews 11:1- faith is the evidence of things unseen, the substance of things hoped for. According to Merriam Webster *chuckle* evidence is: 1 a : an outward sign : INDICATION b : something that furnishes proof : so, true faith shows evidence, if &quot;faith&quot; does not show evidence (which is, keep in mind, an outward sign or something that furnishes proof) then it is not faith; baptism is an outward sign which will, by someone who truly has faith, and thus is truly saved, be shown. So, it is logical that one who is not baptised does not have faith, and thus is not saved. <br>
<br>
Futhermore, i concede, those particular verses have nothing to do with baptism, but those are not the only verses dealing with salvation, either. Take into consideration the following:<br>
Acts 2:38   Then Peter said unto them, Repent, and be baptized every one of you in the name of Jesus Christ for the remission of sins, and ye shall receive the gift of the Holy Ghost;<br>
Acts 22:16    And now why tarriest thou? arise, and be baptized, and wash away thy sins, calling on the name of the Lord;<br>
1 Peter 3:21 The like figure whereunto even baptism doth also now save us (not the putting away of the filth of the flesh, but the answer of a good conscience toward God,) by the resurrection of Jesus Christ:<br>
Romans 6:4 Therefore we are buried with him by baptism into death: that like as Christ was raised up from the dead by the glory of the Father, even so we also should walk in newness of life. Just becuase a few verses, or even the majority of verses, dealing with salvation make no mention of baptism, does not mean that baptism is not necessary, for, as we see in these verses, it truly is.<br>
