<br>
Luke 3:22 does shows the Holy Spirit descend on Jesus in bodily form, but I ask, what does that prove? It is obvious that this doesn't happen at every baptism so why was Jesus special. I submit that this was the start of Jesus' ministry. This was God showing that He blessed what His Son was doing. And it is quite obvious, as I stated in my case, that Jesus did not have to be saved. So, it is a fallacy to use the baptism of Jesus as a case for baptism into salvation because Jesus didn't have to be saved. I find it ironic that Merriam Webster's wording of the word evidence simply proves my point. Notice, it is an outward sign. It is something that identifies us with Christ, like I stated in my case. Also, the right wording of Hebrews 11:1 is &quot;Faith is the substance of things hoped for, the evidence of things not seen.&quot;  Now, read on. Notice that not once person is said to have faith and been baptized in that whole chapter. It is only &quot;By faith...&quot; It is funny that it only mention faith. &quot;Faith is...the evidence of things not seen.&quot; Notice that it doesn't say baptism there. And whitetigress did not show a link anywhere of not being baptized directly correlating with a lack of faith. <br>
<br>
I submit the following verses as a direct support of my argument.<br>
<br>
Acts 10:44-48<br>
While Peter yet spake these words, the Holy Ghost fell on all them which heard the word. <br>
And they of the circumcision which believed were astonished, as many as came with Peter, because that on the Gentiles also was poured out the gift of the Holy Ghost. <br>
For they heard them speak with tongues, and magnify God. Then answered Peter, <br>
Can any man forbid water, that these should not be baptized, which have received the Holy Ghost as well as we? <br>
<br>
Notice that these believers were instilled with the Holy Spirit even before they were baptized. And perhaps the most popular example of this is the thief on the cross. He was never baptized, but, in the words of Jesus, “To day shalt thou be with me in paradise.”<br>
<br>
Luke 7:48-50<br>
And he said unto her, Thy sins are forgiven. <br>
And they that sat at meat with him began to say within themselves, Who is this that forgiveth sins also? <br>
And he said to the woman, Thy faith hath saved thee; go in peace. <br>
<br>
Again, notice that Jesus never told her to go get baptized. Now, you may wonder, is the Bible conflicting with itself, because whitetigress’ verses seem to portray a different light on baptism. This is because the disciples were doing as they should. They were preaching repentance and baptism, both of which are done in obedience to God. And indeed, they preached very strongly that this should be done, almost to the point where it sounds synonymous with baptism, yet there is a distinct difference, as the above verses point out. I leave you with a few more…<br>
